spanGrp.span: Wohei neneeninee, neito'eino', niiyou nuhu' nono'eiteen.
Well you all, my relatives, all of us of the Arapaho tribe.
Wonoo3ee' neito'ei, tei'yoonoh'o', neisiihoho', hoonoo3oo'o' neniteeno'.
My relatives are many, children, grandchildren, other people.
Woow niiP hiiwoonhehe' nuhu' heecxooyeinoo' hiine'etiit.
Now today, [here we are at this stage] up to which Arapaho life has evolved.
[here we are] inside this school building.
The children are still being taught the Arapaho language.
Well they come into [this classroom], however many of them.
If they hold on to it, if they remember it, well then they'll gradually catch on to it.
They are going along with the White man's way of life.
That's the place they're at now.
[We know] how different the White man's ways are, all the ways they do thing.
you see sitting right here a typewriter, it tells you things;
These are the things we're teaching [our kids] now.
That's how life is advancing, in the White man way.
But then here's our Arapaho language.
How the Indians got along up to now.
Everyone just followed the crowd [using English] without thinking about it.
follow the crowd, just do what others do
[Now] all they can do is repeat words, Arapaho words [and try to learn a little bit].
Here I am, I grew up with the Arapaho language.
I was just a little boy, and folks started speaking Arapaho to me.
That's how I learned it for myself.
That was how- that was how I came to speak Arapaho.
Hoo3oo'o' tei'yoonoh'o', heeneecxooyeihino', hiit nih'iineeneti3etino' hinono'eitiit.
The other children, whatever their ages, we spoke Arapaho with each other.
We would argue back and forth, we would speak Arapaho about things.
We picked up on Arapaho [that way].
And that's how we came to know [our language], after [our parents] started teaching us, at least as I remember it.
I woke up in the morning to [Arapaho language], because I was Arapaho.
“I'm going to talk Arapaho,” [I just thought to myself automatically].
My grandfather and my grandmother raised me.
I was raised by my grandparents.
[my grandfather] put it down on the floor.
You're going to fetch some water;
And I didn't know what he was saying.
Well water goes in the bucket.
Well in that direction, he pointed towards the river maybe.
Maybe I'm supposed to go het water.
“Well that's what he said,” [I thought to myself].
Well then I picked up the bucket.
Then I went outside, down to the river.
Well just where he had put the bucket down, I put it down.
“Well, that's it, good, good,” [he said to me].
Wohei beebeet niiteinootee' nuhu', nihce'no'uP... beebeet niiteinootee', ce'ciinenowoo.
Well right where it had been standing, I- I put it back down right where it has been standing.
[When I got back] then I thought about [where to put the bucket] too, [before I put it down].
Right here, that's not where it was standing, [that's not] how it's supposed to be.
so then I guess I put it down there again.
Well then I picked it up, and then I put it down.
good, that's it,” [he said to me].
then I knew what he was saying, because- there wasn't any wood.
Then I went and chopped wood.
Once I was finished chopping wood, then I put it here in the wood box.
Noh nehe' wootii ne'nih'iisiini niiteicesise'inowoo nuhu' hinono'eitiit.
And this [way] I guess that was how I gradually started to know Arapaho.
Well [the elders] would use lots of long Arapaho words.
And at the start I didn't know them.
Finally I picked up on them.
Then I really started [learning], I really and truly spoke Arapaho.
Wohei huut nih'iiP no'oeteiniihi', niiyou nuhu' neyei3eino'oowu'.
Well here ... down by the river, there's this school.
Then I started going to school with the English language.
That's when I started having some problems.
Once in a while I would understand some English words [when they spoke].
I guess slowly I just picked it up.
When I started learning, I had a tough time.
Finally I caught on to it;
then I had two languages: Arapaho or English.
[a child] comes in here and learns a certain amount.
But then they go back outside [of class],
Next time, they come- the next day, they come back in here.
“Well, what are we going to do?”
others don't even give it a thought
Whenever they go home, [they only hear] English.
Wherever there's a gathering, there is [only] English spoken.
Even where we hold ceremonies, [the leader] doesn't know it: they only speak English.
I imagine things are going to be different fifteen years on from now, in a few years.
I, and other [older people], they are speaking Arapaho.
They will- it looks like [the language] is coming to an end.
Here I am, I want to still live a long time;
I want to see how things are going to be in the future.
I am pushing the children to do their best.
push s.o. do do their best
“Okay try- try to speak Arapaho, try to learn the things I'm telling you,” [I say to them].
They just stare at me in confusion.
stare at, in confusion, blank look
Howoo neisiihoho' wo'ei3 nih'iinoonooP nooxeihi' tootohuucxooyeiniihi', heene'ineebe hinono'eitiit.
Even my grandchildren or ??? ......[my kids and grandkids] of whatever age, “You should know Arapaho!” [I say to them].
They don't know what I'm saying.
This thing which [the teachers] are teaching you, that's it [writing].
Here is how it's written, how it's written.
Also here they are [the students], they try to write Arapaho, Arapaho words
Noh hookoh... niine'eehek nuhu' tei'yoonoh'o', heetn-iihokootenou'u xonou heeyowuuhu' hokootouu3iihi'.
And because...here are these children, they will change it immediately every time that the generations change, [language changes].
it is good that it's being done white-man way [written].
Tou3ooku3, heetou3ooku3, nenee' hee3ebiini heni'iine'etiino' nih'oo3ou'u hitei'towoo.
Anyway, anyway, from now on- we're going to be living with the White Man's teachings.
And we'll be strong thanks to [those teachings];
we'll look out for each other.
look out for/protect/stand up for e.o.
And the White man is strong;
That's it: keep trying [to pick up] the White man's ways.
His teachings, the things Whites are teaching you, that's good.
Then you will develop to the point that [you're ready for] higher education.
grow up to reach a point
This is the state that the Arapaho language is in.
You all will help it out.
You will learn about it for your relatives.
learn about s.t. for s.o. else
Howoo noono'uxotiinee hinee heneeceebin, hecesneeceeno', noh heenei'isiihi'.
You will bring it back to our Council, the tribal committees, and so forth.
you will- whoever- whichever ones are occupying an important position, some of them are speaking Arapaho.
